@jaraco, @takluyver has proposed that we elevate the `entry_points.txt` file format to being a PyPA interoperability specification, rather than being an internal implementation detail of `setuptools`: https://github.com/pypa/python-packaging-user-guide/pull/390

I'm inclined to say yes, since it will better allow new publishing tools like `flit` to declare plugins for existing applications that use `pkg_resources` for plugin management, and also allow new projects like `entrypoints` to experiment with alternate approaches to reading and caching the runtime lookup entry point metadata, without risking any compatibility breaks for current `pkg_resources` users.

However, I'd like to get an explicit +1 from you before we go ahead and do that. The main consequence is that if you later decided you wanted to change the entry points file format, that would now have to go through the PEP process, rather than being a purely internal setuptools design discussion.

As discussed on https://github.com/openzipkin/b3-propagation/issues/21 and first implemented here: https://github.com/openzipkin/brave/blob/master/brave/src/main/java/brave/propagation/B3SingleFormat.java https://github.com/openzipkin/brave/blob/master/brave/src/test/java/brave/propagation/B3SingleFormatTest.java

Let's support at least reading "b3" header from a single string, most commonly traceid-spanid-1
It would also be nice to support optionally writing this, especially in message providers or others with constrained environments.

Brave currently has a property like this, but its name could change with feedback:
```java
    /**
     * When true, only writes a single {@link B3SingleFormat b3 header} for outbound propagation.
     *
     * <p>Use this to reduce overhead. Note: normal {@link Tracing#propagation()} is used to parse
     * incoming headers. The implementation must be able to read "b3" headers.
     */
    public Builder b3SingleFormat(boolean b3SingleFormat) {
      this.b3SingleFormat = b3SingleFormat;
      return this;
}
```

The recently pushed out IE11 security update from february 10th 2015 causes a javascript error in the edit template of the OrderedSelectWidget.  Users might not notice the error and upon save already selected items in the widget are lost: and empty widget is saved back tot the content item. 

Specifically these lines cause the problem in IE11 in orderedselect_input.pt:

    // create virtual node with suitable attributes
    var newNode = document.createElement("input");

    .......

    newAttr = document.createAttribute("type");
    newAttr.nodeValue = "hidden";
    newNode.setAttributeNode(newAttr);

It will throw a  "member not found" error. See attached screenshot.

Setting other attributes using setAttributeNode are fine, but setting type="hidden" gives problems. My temporary fix in a customer project where I have a controlled environment on the browser versions used (latest IE11, recent Firefox), is using "setAttribute":

    var newNode = document.createElement("input");
    newNode.setAttribute("name", name.replace(/-/g, '.')+':list');
    newNode.setAttribute("type", "hidden");
    newNode.setAttribute("value",toSel.options[i].value );

But I haven't been able to verify this for other/older browsers and check for compatibility of the .setAttribute method.

![setattributenode](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/394784/6286011/04aa730e-b903-11e4-81eb-bf4683f34297.gif)

